{"ts":"2026-07-06T23:18:28.374Z","author":"maintainer-agent","op":"create","patch":[{"op":"replace","path":"/body","value":"pm restore <id> <target> can rewrite an item back to a prior version, but there is no READ-ONLY way to inspect what an item looked like at a given version or timestamp. Agents auditing provenance today must either run a mutating restore (then restore back) or manually fold JSON Patch entries from pm history --full — expensive, error-prone, and impossible to compose in pipelines.\n\nProposal: a non-mutating projection flag on the read path:\n- pm get <id> --at <version|ISO timestamp> reconstructs the item state by replaying the append-only history stream up to the target and renders it through the normal get projection (json/toon, --tree excluded).\n- Output marks the projection clearly (as_of_version, as_of_timestamp, reconstructed: true) so downstream tooling can never confuse a historical view with current state.\n- Reuses the same replay engine as pm restore (shared SDK primitive; no second replay implementation) so restore and read-projection can never diverge.\n- SDK: expose as a first-class read primitive (getItemAt) so custom tools built on the SDK get time-travel reads for free — a prerequisite for building VCS-like systems on pm primitives.\n\nThis closes the read half of the durability story: the append-only hash-chained history already guarantees every version is recorded; this makes every version cheaply inspectable."},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/id","value":"pm-hib1"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/title","value":"Point-in-time read projection: pm get --at <version|timestamp> renders reconstructed historical item state without mutating"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/description","value":""},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/type","value":"Feature"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/status","value":"open"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/priority","value":2},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/tags","value":["agent-ux","history","immutable-record"]},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/created_at","value":"2026-07-06T23:18:28.374Z"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/updated_at","value":"2026-07-06T23:18:28.374Z"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/author","value":"maintainer-agent"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/estimated_minutes","value":240},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/acceptance_criteria","value":"pm get <id> --at <version> and --at <timestamp> return the reconstructed state with reconstructed:true and as_of_* fields in both json and toon; reconstruction reuses the restore replay helper (single implementation, verified by test); invalid/future targets fail with a structured error listing the valid version range; SDK exposes the same primitive with reference docs; works after history-compact (checkpoint-aware replay); no mutation, no lock, no history entry is written by the read"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/parent","value":"pm-o2kc"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/risk","value":"low"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/confidence","value":"high"},{"op":"add","path":"/metadata/dependencies","value":[{"id":"pm-9yfo","kind":"related","created_at":"2026-07-06T23:18:28.374Z"},{"id":"pm-hu11","kind":"related","created_at":"2026-07-06T23:18:28.374Z"},{"id":"pm-tqel","kind":"related","created_at":"2026-07-06T23:18:28.374Z"}]}],"before_hash":"3cc22dff72be7b14824654a7a64ea62b04799939b2fee54c1b5f52ca60bf6df0","after_hash":"aea99af25b7f3fd31102c291e2b6e6f092d54cdf8103c49e6f7bfcc6bb1e96fd","message":"Long-horizon durability planning: read-only time-travel projection gap"}
{"ts":"2026-07-06T23:36:46.759Z","author":"maintainer-agent","op":"append","patch":[{"op":"replace","path":"/body","value":"pm restore <id> <target> can rewrite an item back to a prior version, but there is no READ-ONLY way to inspect what an item looked like at a given version or timestamp. Agents auditing provenance today must either run a mutating restore (then restore back) or manually fold JSON Patch entries from pm history --full — expensive, error-prone, and impossible to compose in pipelines.\n\nProposal: a non-mutating projection flag on the read path:\n- pm get <id> --at <version|ISO timestamp> reconstructs the item state by replaying the append-only history stream up to the target and renders it through the normal get projection (json/toon, --tree excluded).\n- Output marks the projection clearly (as_of_version, as_of_timestamp, reconstructed: true) so downstream tooling can never confuse a historical view with current state.\n- Reuses the same replay engine as pm restore (shared SDK primitive; no second replay implementation) so restore and read-projection can never diverge.\n- SDK: expose as a first-class read primitive (getItemAt) so custom tools built on the SDK get time-travel reads for free — a prerequisite for building VCS-like systems on pm primitives.\n\nThis closes the read half of the durability story: the append-only hash-chained history already guarantees every version is recorded; this makes every version cheaply inspectable.\n\n## Scope note 2026-07-07 — workspace-level projection (future phase)\nItem-scoped get --at is phase 1. A later phase can generalize the same reconstruction to workspace-level reads (list/context --at <timestamp>) for retrospectives and flow analysis over historical states; that phase must be index-backed (pm-801d) to avoid replaying every stream, and pairs naturally with the flow metrics in pm-pee5. Do not start it before item-scoped --at ships and the read index exists — filed as a scope note here (not a separate item) to keep one owner for time-travel reads."},{"op":"replace","path":"/metadata/updated_at","value":"2026-07-06T23:36:46.759Z"}],"before_hash":"aea99af25b7f3fd31102c291e2b6e6f092d54cdf8103c49e6f7bfcc6bb1e96fd","after_hash":"7121a6348ae27a484faa11260cca852f3a22f1319ed563c6b4dede3f1ef2b9bd"}
